The Pride of India exhibition, being held as part of the 103rd Indian Science Congress here, is a one-stop window to the cutting-edge technologies shaping modern India.Inaugurated on Sunday, the exhibition has nearly 180 participants and there is a special gallery called Hall of Pride, dedicated to the former President A.P.J. Abdul Kalam.Some of the personalities featured in the hall in the earlier editions included Vikram Sarabhai, Satish Dhawan, Acharya Prafulla Chandra Ray, M. Visvesvaraya, Jawaharlal Nehru.ISRO has a section displaying models of its launch vehicles and the Mars Orbiter Mission, Chandrayan-I, apart from posters highlighting the achievements.Laboratories affiliated to the Council of Scientific and Industrial Research (CSIR) were present showcasing their achievements but one of the biggest representation was by the Defence Research and Development Organisation (DRDO) which has more than 50 laboratories affiliated to it of which 36 are participating.Harsh Vardhan, Union Minister of Science and Technology and Earth Sciences, inaugurated the DRDO Pavilion and praised DRDOâ€™s contributions to defence technology.Models of various defence-related objects were on display. This included Advanced Torpedo Systems, Autonomous Underwater Vehicle, Snake Robot, CBRN Remotely Operated Vehicle, CBRN Unmanned Ground Vehicle and Mobile Autonomous Robotic Systems which are some of the star attractions.Biomedical equipments, various missile models , models of battle tank, Arjun, advanced Avionics Sensors and Systems, LCA Tejas fighter aircraft model, INSAS Rifle and a host of military equipments were on display at the DRDO galleryRailways is also participating and South Western Railway has depicted images of different types of locomotives operating in the country.